name: places/ChIJJf_w4ScZ2jERDtWtsUivsWw/reviews/ChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUR3M2V6V0lBEAE
text:
{'text': 'Lou Shang’s Full Breakfast @ Lou Shang

Having seen this in so many social media posts, I thought it was quite novel but probably just cafe-ish. I was kinda right.

Seeing the decor up close was quite something, if you’ve lived through this era you would find it a blast to the past! The door being framed as an elevator is also a great touch. The false walls give room for a small light behind each door, giving a sense of being in a lived-in corridor. If this was the exterior, then 冰糖糖水办公室 would show the interior.

That aside, I went for the full breakfast(I know, it’s just a breakfast platter, nothing fusion) but I found it kinda lacking. The Rosti was overly soft and lifting the pieces you could tell it was drooping abit. The curry mayo also basically tasted like Creme Fraiche, couldn’t really taste much curry. The scrambled eggs were fine, so were the mushrooms. The chicken cheese sausage were also very ordinary. The best parts were the toast and the otah.

The toast was crispy and chewy, with a nice slab of butter on top. Just good in general. The otah was the only thing out of the ordinary in your standard breakfast platter and it stood out. A little sweeter compared to most otahs and alot spicier, had nice texture and was smooth enough to cut without being gel-like. Watch out for the kick if you can’t take spice.

Overall, for the price you could do worse, but you could do better too. Visit for the decor and maybe the fusion food, just not for this. Maybe order something else with otah on the side? I’ll go a little lighter on it for the novelty, it’s a place you should visit once(maybe with your parents).

7/10', 'languageCode': 'en'}

name: places/ChIJJf_w4ScZ2jERDtWtsUivsWw/reviews/ChdDSUhNMG9nS0VPYjQ1ZDNxMUlxLTZ3RRAB
text:
{'text': 'During my younger days living in the Redhill rental flats, there were residents who cooked and sold food to their neighbours. The Malay residents would sell nasi lemak, mee rebus, and curry puffs. The Chinese residents would prepare bubur cha cha, red bean soup, green bean soup, and economic mee and bee hoon. As the theme of the café is nostalgic HDB corridors, the menu could consider including food that was commonly sold by residents in those days. These dishes can be elevated with a modern twist and included in the menu.

The current selection of main dishes on the menu is limited. If the proportion of ketchup in the soft shell chilli crab pasta sauce were reduced, the dish would taste more authentic.
The dry laksa supreme is commonly served at many eateries and may not be a strong crowd-puller.
The smoked duck prata pizza is a creative dish—it resembles a pizza but tastes like a Peking duck wrap, making it a standout item.
The polo bun with otah is also a well-matched combination.
The café’s lighting could be enhanced to create a more vibrant and inviting atmosphere.', 'languageCode': 'en'}

text: {'text': 'Made reservation because I had a party of 7 pax. Staff were all very attentive and they were kind enough to let us bring in our own Birthday cake for cake cutting. name: places/ChIJJf_w4ScZ2jERDtWtsUivsWw/reviews/ChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUR3MWZ1RGZBEAE
text: {'text': 'The menu offers a variety of food and drinks, with each item clearly listing its ingredients. The cafe has an HDB-inspired concept, creating a warm and homely atmosphere. I absolutely loved it and would definitely visit again to try their breakfast or lunch dishes! ❤️\n\nThe staff are kind and friendly, even offering to take pictures for us—a thoughtful touch that shows great attention to detail.', 'languageCode': 'en'}
